atic final majorVersion from java.version. I might need to run CleanUtil in an isolated JVM with the -Djava.version=1.8 flag. But can I actually set the java.version property before class initialization? I could try setting it before loading CleanUtil, but I worry it might already be loaded by previous tests. \\n\\nShould I create a separate test file? Per the rules, each dynamic-access class requires its own Java test file. A custom ClassLoader could help load a CleanUtil copy after setting java.version. I’m considering these options!\\n\\n**Considering Java versioning in tests**\\n\\nI’m exploring whether I can use the public API in a forked Java process with the -Djava.version=1.8.0 flag. But I think the command line for java.version might not be overridable; -D might get ignored? I need to test this. If I fork a process, I wonder if the coverage agent will trace it. \\n\\nMy goal is to cover the Java8 branch without losing the Java9 coverage that’s already established. I might set the java.version property in a test that loads CleanUtil first. But I'm balancing how to manage coverage so that previous progress isn’t lost!\\n\\n**Exploring Java branches in testing**\\n\\nGiven that static initialization only happens once per JVM, forcing a Java8 branch could mean that Java9 call sites won’t be covered in the same run. Using separate JVMs for each test class seems necessary, but it might not mesh well with Gradle's JUnit setup, which often uses the same fork per module. \\n\\nI think I need to explore options for covering both branches simultaneously. Perhaps creating an in-memory JavaCompiler could help, but I’m unsure about the dynamic class loading support. Loading CleanUtil into an isolated URLClassLoader after setting its java.version to 1.8.0 might work!\\n\\n**Evaluating coverage options**\\n\\nI’m considering what happens if we switch branches — coverage could flip, which isn't good. I think I need to combine approaches and maybe look into custom class load