JPZhX-iklSDwYzR71fgocadq2VZwzs_qHOTSVyNdkh8igA6fyio809Of4XJNzjekcA==\\\",\\\"summary\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering test ordering**\\\\n\\\\nI’m thinking about how testing should be structured after child tests. Maybe after those, the system test could load the real one. If the first test is a direct system test, it would cover Java 9. On the other hand, if an isolated test runs second, that would target Java 8. I want to make sure the tests are organized logically to ensure comprehensive coverage.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating Java configurations**\\\\n\\\\nI'm looking at restoring the Java version and deciding if it's okay to add \\\\\\\"--add-opens\\\\\\\" in build.gradle. I wonder if I could skip it by not invoking setAccessible, but if I don't add it, I encounter throws that leave certain lines uncovered. So, I'll need to add it. But when running a native image, those arguments become irrelevant. I'm considering custom ClassLoader support, catching any UnsupportedFeatureError, and ensuring proper resource reading from CleanUtil path. I'll use readAllBytes for reading bytes, but I hope the parent exposes the class resource!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Implementing loadClass method**\\\\n\\\\nI'm considering implementing a synchronized loadClass method. If the class name isn't CLEAN_UTIL_CLASS_NAME, I'll return the super version. I need to find a loaded class or load it if it isn't already loaded. If I resolve, I'll call resolveClass. For finding classes, if it's only for the target, I’ll use getParent().getResourceAsStream for loading bytes. But what if the parent is null? It’ll throw an IOException. I also need to manage Method.invoke calls, which might add extra dynamic access call sites. I wonder how the TCK will track this!\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_T541pIKNTgqa0G13gCpBmzxs|fc_01d3ce057da11f900169fe55d61da8819d90a7c65356365b