  super(urls, parent);\\n        }\\n\\n        @Override\\n        protected Class<?> loadClass(String name, boolean resolve) throws ClassNotFoundException {\\n            if (!CLEAN_UTIL_CLASS_NAME.equals(name)) {\\n                return super.loadClass(name, resolve);\\n            }\\n\\n            synchronized (getClassLoadingLock(name)) {\\n                Class<?> loadedClass = findLoadedClass(name);\\n                if (loadedClass == null) {\\n                    loadedClass = findClass(name);\\n                }\\n                if (resolve) {\\n                    resolveClass(loadedClass);\\n                }\\n                return loadedClass;\\n            }\\n        }\\n    }\\n\"}]}\n2070:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Evaluating Java9 legacy coverage**\\n\\nI'm considering the impact of legacy settings, where covering five might mean losing three, leaving us with only Java9 sites, which seems unfavorable. I wonder if this means we can track cumulatively across attempts. It mentions no changes in the remaining total after previous attempts. I’m thinking about improving the setup to focus purely on legacy. Can we separate original Java9 and legacy tests? I’m not sure if JaCoCo can help, but what if I defined a custom classloader for the instrumented bytes?\\n\\n**Adjusting Java runtime path**\\n\\nI’m looking into whether the Java runtime class path is impacted by the module. It seems that maybe the dynamic agent isn’t covering everything since the source line in the duplicate class isn't being mapped properly. It should be! I think I need to include a comment regarding child-first loading. So, it looks like I need to make some edits to address this and ensure everything works smoothly.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_01d3ce057da11f900169fe56bb1f58819db508ce77601d4f01\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\