o define multiple test tasks to manage different Java versions. I'm trying to prioritize the legacy coverage properly.\\n\\n**Exploring TCK dynamic reporting**\\n\\nI’m considering whether the TCK dynamic report could include all test tasks, but it seems like the `javaTest` task may execute them all. I need to check the plugin to confirm. Configuring the default `test` to fork each test method might help, but I can't set two `java.version` values in one task. Creating a custom `legacyCleanUtilTest` task could be beneficial. Perhaps Gradle supports a way to set system properties right before the test method runs? I’m also wondering if JUnit’s ordering could assist, but I might need a new approach altogether.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_01d3ce057da11f900169fe56e57de4819d9fd8fe3c8f1b8c2a\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp_lb85DiB4S917oXZUUvqNWwC3fwaLzeeQIvY0l63qw5WlWBaAdEzieIcbuE46pY_Zd7cBDn2Q6YtpTN6XMG8tExSWFi-HN1C9zXulVGN0NZABDd3e-OZcvhKom5lGwuk6G58NQ6_G7mn5QVW8WYI_l5bWNIrPldnO3GznH5_OjvZ-rCr-J3UY-YIt4lZA3VrDG0Amz86mlNklNhwc_MtKq1AkA8wQAXSWIeYl860RBQv_7saL0_BSAESeAOWDQhe0qFYecEI5fWCUVnR4v75k72HBoGaeNz_RKbiWFYKayX0wYm7VuXRKCs15_-xK122qayQAo9vDARtYEKzHEDbzBfzcy75ME_d2Gy0OBr1Fq7YcVK3NnmjLXJhTuHda7e6v8_cZu27Q6YbC_ExFA8r_5coSqz-683eRLQ-418KGy7HDtci4dMYN3lPb4Ru35eGVzind1KEfPAcxx9VfoBMMZ53n7Qx3ianCPwpU5AutSaY0cfHVagiLGmu0qo4x7MPH6pYBxLTBFsqFlBo-gsiJX8QnI83fUsFTyjW7apJtEUEfwtsyBy2k1SkMyQrmgAJcVLxqQpTUYMqqqvkrQIjhiKn2CjzFaUrCT7GI0408-C3mrp_5Xt5vQ0mY65N_umLm_7OvFWNNap8cCIOCYUzM9vNs2IfvXsHxk8HoxavCV_Gpb4-qjXVGkMc9sSK0pOFwsayM9nt7zgIYpNsED7-8TFeM4wvywzzW42Z4fY4thLtWUmpOPm4tVaGuAUFfpWHpjJuyAU-ZySVNYa7OX1WKcR02QtQT-zfJIPQ8SI7uW8RYDcwa8Fi6HSazQMHd1tx58hcr_fX7eIxJvPnRBIR0hBGXjsLJtyPzPaT26SQtSBkutA3SKNzb_BFKtDh0eVpux0bVSccRsCxNbmTbk7dxrjdSvqPHT-n4A6hx84QyW-M6NFrHGfxsImsaFJxghr4CKzo-Gsl_VgVpgG0TTEicwSy7sLfVf1SHiajLJtEh-1UBsXo015yX8EQOdDA5tdJ8KYyHjZNeBW0gBULa4gtfANNTHyKSiX32sU7-DQWY4VyLvImrgYva9GANmFCjulXJVVcTpqvW7lSJB6cIpTe5BP4