test classes and adjusting Gradle settings, but this could complicate things since JUnit can’t vary system properties before loading classes.\\n\\n**Evaluating Java testing strategy**\\n\\nI’m considering whether we can create `CleanUtilLegacyTest` without importing `CleanUtil`. It seems like we should have dedicated test files for each dynamic-access class. Currently, there's just `CleanUtilTest`, and I don’t want to add an additional file. There’s a lot of complexity around JUnit ordering and Java 9's URLClassLoader. If I run tests in separate JVMs, could that help with coverage? Gradle might allow me to define multiple test tasks to manage different Java versions. I'm trying to prioritize the legacy coverage properly.\\n\\n**Exploring TCK dynamic reporting**\\n\\nI’m considering whether the TCK dynamic report could include all test tasks, but it seems like the `javaTest` task may execute them all. I need to check the plugin to confirm. Configuring the default `test` to fork each test method might help, but I can't set two `java.version` values in one task. Creating a custom `legacyCleanUtilTest` task could be beneficial. Perhaps Gradle supports a way to set system properties right before the test method runs? I’m also wondering if JUnit’s ordering could assist, but I might need a new approach altogether.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_01d3ce057da11f900169fe56e57de4819d9fd8fe3c8f1b8c2a\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp_lb85DiB4S917oXZUUvqNWwC3fwaLzeeQIvY0l63qw5WlWBaAdEzieIcbuE46pY_Zd7cBDn2Q6YtpTN6XMG8tExSWFi-HN1C9zXulVGN0NZABDd3e-OZcvhKom5lGwuk6G58NQ6_G7mn5QVW8WYI_l5bWNIrPldnO3GznH5_OjvZ-rCr-J3UY-YIt4lZA3VrDG0Amz86mlNklNhwc_MtKq1AkA8wQAXSWIeYl860RBQv_7saL0_BSAESeAOWDQhe0qFYecEI5fWCUVnR4v75k72HBoGaeNz_RKbiWFYKayX0wYm7VuXRKCs15_-xK122qayQAo9vDARtYEKzHEDbzBfzcy75ME_d2Gy0OBr1Fq7YcVK3NnmjLXJhTuHda7e6v8_cZu27Q6YbC_ExFA8r_5coSqz-683eRLQ-418KGy7HDtci4dMYN3lPb4Ru35eGVzind1KEfPAcxx9VfoBMMZ53n7Qx3ianCPwpU5AutSaY0cfHVagi